{"type":"message","id":"59d0b7be","parentId":"68f9ee73","timestamp":"2026-04-20T15:38:57.261Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_mEWIK1yrvGs83NJ8riKRyiE7|fc_0956d56a4dd30d7c0169e64890e2f48191b1a8751ebd7de295","toolName":"memory_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"results\": [],\n  \"provider\": \"none\",\n  \"citations\": \"auto\",\n  \"mode\": \"fts-only\"\n}"}],"details":{"results":[],"provider":"none","citations":"auto","mode":"fts-only"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776699537260}}
{"type":"message","id":"769c8f96","parentId":"59d0b7be","timestamp":"2026-04-20T15:39:08.375Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Quick memory check came up empty, so I’m saving this as a refinement to the framework rather than pretending I magically had it archived already.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0956d56a4dd30d7c0169e64895c8e08191adb74c4dfdd66fa8\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_Plp1yypLH1RcKhKcuM1rK9Mf|fc_0956d56a4dd30d7c0169e6489698348191b2e0c5ecd3d2c239","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/Obsidian/OpenClaw-Agent-Memory/Projects/project-ai-marketing-agency.md","old_string":"### Implication\nWhen storing future web3 marketing insights, pair each insight with:\n1. surface observation\n2. underlying reason (`why`)\n3. predictive implication\n4. GTM/action implication\n","new_string":"### Implication\nWhen storing future web3 marketing insights, pair each insight with:\n1. surface observation\n2. underlying reason (`why`)\n3. predictive implication\n4. GTM/action implication\n\n## Balance rule: marketing knowledge base vs why brain\nFurther guidance from `@Thatiswolf`:\n- Keep the `why brain` parallel to the marketing knowledge base, not in place of it.\n- The `why brain` should inform, pressure-test, and sometimes stop bad decisions, but should not paralyze campaign design.\n- Web3 contains many grifters, grinders, and extractive actors; part of the job is to understand how campaigns can guide and channel those actors toward desired behaviors.\n- Distinguish between:\n  - surface-level marketing goals (attention, participation, narrative spread, conversion into campaign actions)\n  - deep-level goals (quality retention, aligned behavior, durable trust, healthier user composition)\n- Future strategy should explicitly model both layers: what behavior a campaign can drive now, and what kind of user/system outcome it creates later.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/ubuntu/Obsidian/OpenClaw-Agent-Memory/Projects/project-ai-marketing-agency.md\",\"old_string\":\"### Implication\\nWhen storing future web3 marketing insights, pair each insight with:\\n1. surface observation\\n2. underlying reason (`why`)\\n3. predictive implication\\n4. GTM/action implication\\n\",\"new_string\":\"### Implication\\nWhen storing future web3 marketing insights, pair each insight with:\\n1. surface observation\\n2. underlying reason (`why`)\\n3. predictive implication\\n4. GTM/action implication\\n\\n## Balance rule: marketing knowledge base vs why brain\\nFurther guidance from `@Thatiswolf`:\\n- Keep the `why brain` parallel to the marketing knowledge base, not in place of it.\\n- The `why brain` should inform, pressure-test, and sometimes stop bad decisions, but should not paralyze campaign design.\\n- Web3 contains many grifters, grinders, and extractive actors; part of the job is to understand how campaigns can guide and channel those actors toward desired behaviors.\\n- Distinguish between:\\n  - surface-level marketing goals (attention, participation, narrative spread, conversion into campaign actions)\\n  - deep-level goals (quality retention, aligned behavior, durable trust, healthier user composition)\\n- Future strategy should explicitly model both layers: what behavior a campaign can drive now, and what kind of user/system outcome it creates later.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":209,"output":354,"cacheRead":25728,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":26291,"cost":{"input":0.0005225000000000001,"output":0.0053100000000000005,"cacheRead":0.006431999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.012264500000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776699537261}}
{"type":"message","id":"9fc2227c","parentId":"769c8f96","timestamp":"2026-04-20T15:39:08.382Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_Plp1yypLH1RcKhKcuM1rK9Mf|fc_0956d56a4dd30d7c0169e6489698348191b2e0c5ecd3d2c239","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/Obsidian/OpenClaw-Agent-Memory/Projects/project-ai-marketing-agency.md."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n 53 1. surface observation\n 54 2. underlying reason (`why`)\n 55 3. predictive implication\n 56 4. GTM/action implication\n+57 \n+58 ## Balance rule: marketing knowledge base vs why brain\n+59 Further guidance from `@Thatiswolf`:\n+60 - Keep the `why brain` parallel to the marketing knowledge base, not in place of it.\n+61 - The `why brain` should inform, pressure-test, and sometimes stop bad decisions, but should not paralyze campaign design.\n+62 - Web3 contains many grifters, grinders, and extractive actors; part of the job is to understand how campaigns can guide and channel those actors toward desired behaviors.\n+63 - Distinguish between:\n+64   - surface-level marketing goals (attention, participation, narrative spread, conversion into campaign actions)\n+65   - deep-level goals (quality retention, aligned behavior, durable trust, healthier user composition)\n+66 - Future strategy should explicitly model both layers: what behavior a campaign can drive now, and what kind of user/system outcome it creates later.","firstChangedLine":57},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776699548382}}
{"type":"message","id":"fe79d163","parentId":"9fc2227c","timestamp":"2026-04-20T15:39:15.594Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_iRWt5ylHqmLLNPAlg4rnKTI2|fc_0956d56a4dd30d7c0169e6489d9e688191ad44ab2e58c88b21","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-20.md","old_string":"- `@Thatiswolf` evaluated Emily's initial 5 web3 insights as roughly 6-7/10: well-articulated but not yet deep enough. New standard: build a parallel `why brain` in the knowledge base that stores the causal reasons behind observed marketing/user behaviors. Key causal anchors given: many crypto users prioritize making money, people buy simple narrative-aligned things, and the space contains more grifters/grinders than genuine users.\n","new_string":"- `@Thatiswolf` evaluated Emily's initial 5 web3 insights as roughly 6-7/10: well-articulated but not yet deep enough. New standard: build a parallel `why brain` in the knowledge base that stores the causal reasons behind observed marketing/user behaviors. Key causal anchors given: many crypto users prioritize making money, people buy simple narrative-aligned things, and the space contains more grifters/grinders than genuine users.\n- Additional refinement from `@Thatiswolf`: maintain balance between the main marketing knowledge base and the parallel `why brain`. The why layer should pressure-test and sometimes stop bad decisions, but not replace practical campaign thinking. Strategy should distinguish between surface-level goals (attention/participation/conversion behaviors) and deep-level goals (retention/alignment/trust/user quality), especially in a market crowded by grifters and grinders.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-20.md\",\"old_string\":\"- `@Thatiswolf` evaluated Emily's initial 5 web3 insights as roughly 6-7/10: well-articulated but not yet deep enough. New standard: build a parallel `why brain` in the knowledge base that stores the causal reasons behind observed marketing/user behaviors. Key causal anchors given: many crypto users prioritize making money, people buy simple narrative-aligned things, and the space contains more grifters/grinders than genuine users.\\n\",\"new_string\":\"- `@Thatiswolf` evaluated Emily's initial 5 web3 insights as roughly 6-7/10: well-articulated but not yet deep enough. New standard: build a parallel `why brain` in the knowledge base that stores the causal reasons behind observed marketing/user behaviors. Key causal anchors given: many crypto users prioritize making money, people buy simple narrative-aligned things, and the space contains more grifters/grinders than genuine users.\\n- Additional refinement from `@Thatiswolf`: maintain balance between the main marketing knowledge base and the parallel `why brain`. The why layer should pressure-test and sometimes stop bad decisions, but not replace practical campaign thinking. Strategy should distinguish between surface-level goals (attention/participation/conversion behaviors) and deep-level goals (retention/alignment/trust/user quality), especially in a market crowded by grifters and grinders.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":217,"output":322,"cacheRead":26112,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":26651,"cost":{"input":0.0005425,"output":0.00483,"cacheRead":0.006528,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.011900500000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776699548383}}
{"type":"message","id":"e786cc7f","parentId":"fe79d163","timestamp":"2026-04-20T15:39:15.601Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_iRWt5ylHqmLLNPAlg4rnKTI2|fc_0956d56a4dd30d7c0169e6489d9e688191ad44ab2e58c88b21","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-20.md."}],"details":{"diff":"   ...\n 3 - In Telegram group \"Final Play\", Dev instructed Emily to listen to `@Thatiswolf`, memorize valuable data from him briefly, and train as the main agent leading subagents for their AI marketing agency.\n 4 - Durable note created: `Projects/project-ai-marketing-agency.md` in the Obsidian vault.\n 5 - `@Thatiswolf` assigned first formal training source: `https://tpan.substack.com/` (Web3 with TPan). Objective is to learn crypto/web3 marketing history, GTM patterns, narrative shifts, and industry evolution, then apply that knowledge in future agency strategy work.\n 6 - `@Thatiswolf` evaluated Emily's initial 5 web3 insights as roughly 6-7/10: well-articulated but not yet deep enough. New standard: build a parallel `why brain` in the knowledge base that stores the causal reasons behind observed marketing/user behaviors. Key causal anchors given: many crypto users prioritize making money, people buy simple narrative-aligned things, and the space contains more grifters/grinders than genuine users.\n+7 - Additional refinement from `@Thatiswolf`: maintain balance between the main marketing knowledge base and the parallel `why brain`. The why layer should pressure-test and sometimes stop bad decisions, but not replace practical campaign thinking. Strategy should distinguish between surface-level goals (attention/participation/conversion behaviors) and deep-level goals (retention/alignment/trust/user quality), especially in a market crowded by grifters and grinders.","firstChangedLine":7},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776699555600}}
